      <body>-1 

Dropping `=` is actually counter-intuitive and not very Ruby-like. It's even less Rails-like.

It's pretty easy to use:

    @foo.bar = 'baz' and @foo.save

Or if you prefer not to have an `and` (and I can't blame you):

    @foo.set(:bar, 'baz')

Seems pretty straightforward and much shorter, plus it's just an alias for `update_attribute`.</body>
      <body-html>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;-1&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Dropping &lt;code&gt;=&lt;/code&gt; is actually counter-intuitive and not
very Ruby-like. It's even less Rails-like.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It's pretty easy to use:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;
&lt;code&gt;@foo.bar = 'baz' and @foo.save&lt;/code&gt;
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Or if you prefer not to have an &lt;code&gt;and&lt;/code&gt; (and I can't
blame you):&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;
&lt;code&gt;@foo.set(:bar, 'baz')&lt;/code&gt;
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Seems pretty straightforward and much shorter, plus it's just an
alias for &lt;code&gt;update_attribute&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</body-html>
